# 5. Core Entities

---

# 5.1 User Account

## Definition

A User Account represents an authenticated identity registered with SFC.

The account provides access to the platform and manages ownership relationships.

---

## Responsibilities

A User Account manages:

* authentication,
* security,
* ownership,
* creator identity,
* account settings.

---

## Public Visibility

A User Account is not the primary public identity.

The account exists primarily for:

* platform security,
* accountability,
* permissions.

---

## Relationship

A User Account may have:

```
One User Account

    owns

One Creator Identity
```

---

## Future Extensions

A future User Account may represent:

* individuals,
* organizations,
* classrooms,
* teams,
* projects.

---

# 5.2 Creator Identity

## Definition

A Creator Identity represents the person or entity responsible for creating content.

---

## Purpose

The Creator Identity establishes:

* accountability,
* attribution,
* ownership relationship.

---

## Public Visibility

The Creator Identity may be publicly visible.

However:

The Channel is the primary public identity.

---

## Example

```
Creator:

Jane Smith


Channels:

- Woodworking Adventures
- My European Travels
- Science Simplified
```

---

## Relationship

```
User Account

    1 : 1

Creator Identity

    1 : many

Channels
```

---

# 5.3 Channel

## Definition

A Channel is the primary publishing identity on SFC.

A Channel represents the entity that viewers discover, follow, and associate with published content.

---

## Purpose

A Channel provides:

* public identity,
* content organization,
* publisher reputation.

---

## Examples

```
Channel:

The Backyard Workshop


Channel:

Exploring Ancient Civilizations


Channel:

Physics Explained
```

---

## Ownership

A Channel has:

* one owner in MVP,
* future support for multiple collaborators.

---

## User Limits

MVP:

```
Maximum Channels per Creator:

3
```

Future:

Additional Channels may be purchased.

---

## Lifecycle

A Channel has the following states:

```
Active

Archived

Deleted
```

---

## Rules

A Channel:

* cannot be permanently deleted immediately,
* must first be archived,
* deletion requires an explicit request.

---

## Visibility

A Channel may be:

```
Public

Private
```

Private Channels are future-oriented and intended for controlled sharing.

---

## Discoverability

A Channel without published content is not searchable.

Minimum requirement:

```
At least one published Page
```

---

# 5.4 Series

## Definition

A Series is a collection of related Episodes organized around a common theme, topic, or story.

---

## Examples

```
Channel:

Backyard Workshop


Series:

Building My First Sailboat
```

---

## Rules

A Series:

* may initially be empty,
* cannot be published while empty.

---

## Visibility

A Series supports:

```
Public

Restricted

Private
```

---

## Relationship

```
Channel

    contains

Many Series
```

---

## Future Use

A Series may represent:

* a subscription product,
* a course,
* a story universe,
* a content collection.

---

# 5.5 Season

## Definition

A Season is an optional grouping mechanism for Episodes within a Series.

---

## Purpose

Seasons allow creators to organize long-running content.

Example:

```
Series:

Building a House


Season 1:

Planning


Season 2:

Construction


Season 3:

Finishing
```

---

## Rules

Seasons are optional.

Episodes may exist directly under a Series.

---

## Visibility

A Season follows the same visibility rules as other content objects.

---

# 5.6 Episode

## Definition

An Episode is a complete story segment.

An Episode consists of one or more Pages.

---

## Lifecycle

MVP:

```
Draft

Published

Deleted
```

Future:

```
Archived

Scheduled
```

---

## Publishing Requirement

An Episode requires:

```
Page 1 exists

AND

Page 1 is published
```

before the Episode can be published.

---

## Relationship

```
Series

    contains

Episodes
```

or:

```
Series

    contains

Seasons

        contain

        Episodes
```

---

# 5.7 Page

## Definition

A Page is the fundamental storytelling unit inside an Episode.

A Page represents a single scene or moment in the story.

Unlike a traditional document page, an SFC Page is a multimedia composition containing:

* visual elements,
* text,
* animation,
* audio,
* timing,
* transitions,
* interactions.

---

## Purpose

Pages allow creators to structure stories in a format inspired by:

* comic books,
* illustrated books,
* presentations,
* documentaries,
* interactive media.

---

## Page Requirements

An Episode must contain:

```text
Minimum Pages:

1

Maximum Pages:

100 (configurable)
```

---

## Page Numbering

Each Episode must contain:

```text
Page 1
```

Page 1 is mandatory.

---

## Page Ordering

Pages may be reordered by the creator during design.

The order determines playback sequence.

---

## Page Duplication

Creators may:

* duplicate a Page within an Episode,
* copy a Page between Episodes.

A duplicated or copied Page becomes an independent object.

Changes to the copy do not affect the original.

---

## Page Lifecycle

A Page may exist in:

```text
Draft

Published

Deleted
```

---

## Deleted Pages

Deleted Pages:

* are not permanently destroyed immediately,
* are skipped during playback,
* may be restored before permanent removal.

---

# 5.8 Story Component

## Definition

A Story Component is an individual element placed on a Page.

A Page is composed of one or more Story Components.

---

## Examples

A Page may contain:

```text
Page:

"Building the Chair"


Components:

- Title text
- Photo of materials
- Video demonstration
- Audio explanation
- Diagram
```

---

## Component Types

MVP supported types:

### Media Components

* Photo
* GIF
* Video
* Audio

### Text Components

* Editable text boxes

---

## Component Properties

Each Story Component may define:

### Position

The location on the Canvas.

---

### Size

The dimensions of the component.

---

### Playback Order

Defines when the component begins relative to other components.

---

### Timing

Defines:

* start time,
* duration,
* completion behavior.

---

### Effects

MVP effects:

* Zoom in/out
* Scroll left/right
* Scroll top/bottom
* Page peel
* Fade in/out

---

### Overlap Behavior

A component may:

```text
Overlay:

The component covers existing content.


Non-overlay:

The component plays inside its defined area.
```

---

# 5.9 Media Asset

## Definition

A Media Asset is a stored piece of uploaded media that may be used as a Story Component.

---

## Supported MVP Types

```text
Image

GIF

Video

Audio
```

---

## Relationship

A Media Asset:

```text
may be used by multiple Story Components
```

---

## Example

A creator uploads:

```text
chair-building-video.mp4
```

The asset may be used:

* on Page 2,
* Page 5,
* another Episode.

---

## Future Considerations

Future Media Assets may include:

* captions,
* subtitles,
* AI-generated animations,
* alternate formats.

